===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{Han simp|р© җ|f=е·ӣ|t=дё·}}. Originally {{liushu|p|nocap=1}} of the head of an animal with a long mouth and horns. In the oracle bone script, it appeared with or without hair ({{zh-l|*е·ӣ}}), but {{zh-l|*р© җ}}, the form with hair, was the form that was perpetuated.

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*qV-luК”}}; cognate with {{cog|lus|lu||head}}. This word has also been compared with {{cog|map-pro|*qulu|*quluh|head}} ({{cog|ms|hulu}}) and {{cog|tai-pro|*krawкҹІ|*klawкҹІ ~ krawкҹІ|head; hair knot}} ({{cog|th|а№ҖаёҒаёҘа№үаёІ||hair; head}}), and was used by Sagart to support his {{w|Sino-Austronesian languages|Sino-Austronesian hypothesis}}. Compare {{och-l|йҒ“|path, road}} (with the same phonetic component) and its relationship with {{cog|hmx-pro|*klЙҷuЛЈ|*klЙҷuX|road, way}}.

This word was replaced by {{och-l|й ӯ|head}} by the {{w|Warring States}} period, possibly due to early homophony with {{och-l|жүӢ|hand}}.

